	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU-Mercosur negotiations relaunched, Central America negotiations concluded</h1>

			
			<h4>
												07 June 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 4 May 2010 the EC proposed to relaunch the trade negotiations with Mercosur. Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht argued that ‘any agreement must be ambitious, bringing increased access for a range of EU businesses, including agriculture, into the Mercosur region.’ The Commission press release noted that the Mercosur region has a global GDP of €1,300 billion, ‘superior to that of countries like South Korea, India and Russia’ and that ‘Mercosur ranks on [a] par with India and ahead of both Canada and Korea.’ Prior to the economic crisis, EU exports to Mercosur were growing at more than 15% annually. Mercosur is seen as ‘a relatively protected market, both in terms of tariffs and non-tariff barriers.’ Concluding an agreement could thus bring real gains for the EU. Indeed the benefits are projected as ‘an increase of around €4.5 billion of exports per year’, with Mercosur expected to benefit from a similar increase. </p><p>Meanwhile, in a context where agriculture makes up a third of Mercosur exports to the EU and 19.8% of total EU agricultural imports, European farmers’ leaders have ‘called on President Sarkozy to [put] pressure on the European Community to impede the relaunching of negotiations for a free-trade agreement with Mercosur’, arguing that ‘the cost for European agriculture would be too high.’ Particular problems are foreseen in the beef and poultry-meat sectors, with farmers estimating losses of €3-5 billion, with France, the UK, Romania, Hungary and Poland (where the poultry sector accounts for ‘9 to 12% of total agricultural output’) being worst affected. According to EU farmers’ organisations, serious losses would also occur in the beef sector in Belgium, France, the UK, Spain and Ireland. Pork, wheat, citrus fruit and juice imports would also increase. COPA President Padraig Walshe argued that a Mercosur deal ‘would lead to a substantial contraction in the EU agriculture sector threatening 28 million jobs’, while COGECA President Paolo Bruni argued that relaunching the negotiations would ‘send the wrong message’ to the EU’s trading partners and ‘would … be badly received by the poorer developing countries of the world who would see the EU giving preferential access to its market to industrial-sized exporters such as Brazil and Argentina.’</p><p>EU President José Manuel Barroso defended the relaunching of the EU-Mercosur negotiations, arguing that ‘a successful result could offer benefits in creation of jobs and growth for both sides.’ For the EU this would mainly arise from ‘increased access to Mercosur markets for things like telecommunications, financial services and cars.’ According to press reports, these gains ‘would outweigh losses felt by the EU agriculture sector.’ It is also reported in the press that President Sarkozy has drawn support from up to 15 EU member states in urging caution in the treatment of food and agricultural products in the Mercosur negotiations. Emphasis is being placed on carefully reviewing the impact of any potential deal before proceeding with specific commitments. Agriculture Commissioner Dacian Cioloş has acknowledged that the Mercosur negotiations are ‘a sensitive issue for agriculture’ but argues that it is ‘too early to say what the impact on EU farmers could be’. Trade Commissioner De Gucht meanwhile has stressed that ‘the substance has to be right for a deal to come off.’</p><p>Meanwhile, on 18 May the EC announced the conclusion of trade negotiations with six central American countries, to the full satisfaction of both parties. Central American exports to the EU are dominated by agricultural products, notably coffee, bananas and other fruits, with agricultural products accounting for 36% of the region’s exports to the EU.</p><p>In May, Eurostat released a memo highlighting the 25% decline in employment in the EU27 agricultural sector since 2000 (from the equivalent of 14.9 million full-time jobs to 11.2 million full-time jobs). The five member states with the highest employment in the agriculture sector (Poland, Romania, Italy, Spain and France) saw employment in the agriculture sector falling by 11%, 41%, 16%, 17% and 17% respectively. Farmers’ income trends vary considerably across EU member states with, since 2000, real agricultural income per worker increasing in 17 member states and falling in 10. The highest increases occurred in Latvia (+140%), Estonia (+131%), Poland (+107%), the UK (+71%) and Lithuania (+70%). The largest declines were in Denmark (-46%), Italy and Luxembourg (-36%), Ireland (-30%) and the Netherlands (-28%). This gives further background to farmers’ concerns over the impact of the Mercosur agreement on the agriculture sector.</p>
		
		
