				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>There is strong opposition among farmers’ organisations to the relaunching of the Mercosur-EU negotiations, yet as President Barroso clearly pointed out, the gains for the EU in terms of job creation and income growth will outweigh the losses suffered in the agricultural sector. Eurostat figures suggest that farmers’ leaders may be painting a rather bleak picture of the impact of the agreement, since the total level of employment in the agricultural sector is equivalent to only 11.2 million full-time jobs. In addition, employment in the agricultural sector has been subject to an ongoing process of decline since 2000, even in the absence of a Mercosur agreement.</p><p>With the restructuring process in the EU agriculture sector benefiting from substantial levels of public-sector financial support, and employment growth in other sectors likely to exceed losses in the agriculture sector, the greatest impact of any EU-Mercosur agreement is likely to be felt by traditional preferred trading partners such as the ACP. However, these effects will be felt in specific sectors in individual ACP countries (e.g. in the beef sector in Namibia and Botswana, and potentially the sugar sector across the ACP). In this context greater policy emphasis may need to be placed on assisting these sectors to undertake production- and trade-adjustment measures to prepare for the impending changes in the EU’s trade relationship with the Mercosur group. </p>
		</div>
		
